#Models

Lets build all the models. Its nice that each as cross-validated or bootstrapped estimates of the error rates.

Penalized Regression

Build the data matrices.

als.x <- data.matrix(als.df[,-1])
als.y <- data.matrix(als.df[,1])
lambda.grid <- 10^seq(-3,1,length=100)
mod.ridge.cv <- cv.glmnet(als.x,als.y,
                          lambda=lambda.grid,
                          alpha=0)
plot(mod.ridge.cv)

Pull of the One SE lambda value.

lambda.opt <- mod.ridge.cv$lambda.1se
mse.ridge <- with(mod.ridge.cv,cvm[lambda == lambda.opt])

Same for Lasso

mod.lasso.cv <- cv.glmnet(als.x,als.y,
                          lambda=lambda.grid,
                          alpha=1)
plot(mod.lasso.cv)

lambda.opt <- mod.ridge.cv$lambda.1se
mse.lasso <- with(mod.lasso.cv,cvm[lambda == lambda.opt])

How are we doing?

c(mse.ridge,mse.lasso)
## [1] 0.2731422 0.3197143

Interestingridge seems to be winning

Bagged Trees

Now lets try Bagging and Random Forests.

These take a minute to compute, using fours cores to accelerate

numCol <- ncol(als.df)
mod.bag <- randomForest(dFRS ~ .,
                        data=als.df,
                        ntree=500,
                        mtry=numCol-1,
                        n.cores = 4)
mod.bag
## 
## Call:
##  randomForest(formula = dFRS ~ ., data = als.df, ntree = 500,      mtry = numCol - 1, n.cores = 4) 
##                Type of random forest: regression
##                      Number of trees: 500
## No. of variables tried at each split: 369
## 
##           Mean of squared residuals: 0.2525497
##                     % Var explained: 20.95
(mse.bag <- mod.bag$mse[500])
## [1] 0.2525497

Now a random forest. This takes some time too (but not as much time since there are fewer predictors in play at each step).

mod.rf <- randomForest(dFRS ~ .,
                       data=als.df,
                       ntree=500,
                       mtry=(numCol-1)/3)
mod.rf
## 
## Call:
##  randomForest(formula = dFRS ~ ., data = als.df, ntree = 500,      mtry = (numCol - 1)/3) 
##                Type of random forest: regression
##                      Number of trees: 500
## No. of variables tried at each split: 123
## 
##           Mean of squared residuals: 0.2516668
##                     % Var explained: 21.22
(mse.rf <- mod.rf$mse[500])
## [1] 0.2516668

Conclusion for the old methods:

Which one is the best?

c(mse.ridge, mse.lasso, mse.bag,mse.rf)
## [1] 0.2731422 0.3197143 0.2525497 0.2516668

We can see that: Looks as if the edge goes to the Trees: Bagging and Random Forest seem to work equally well, beating out the penalized regresssion algorithms.

#Now for our Boosting model:

n <- nrow(als.df)
numFolds=5
folds <- sample(1:numFolds,n,rep=T)
errs <- numeric(numFolds)
for(fold in 1:numFolds){
  train.df.cv <- als.df[folds != fold,]
  test.df.cv <- als.df[folds == fold,]
}
numTrees <- 1000
theShrinkage <- 0.1
theDepth <- 2
mod.gbm <- gbm(dFRS ~.,
               data=train.df.cv,
               distribution="gaussian", ## for regression
               n.trees=numTrees,
               shrinkage=theShrinkage,
               interaction.depth = theDepth,
               n.cores = 4)
numTreesPred <- 500
prob.gbm <- predict(mod.gbm,
                    newdata=test.df.cv,
                    n.trees=100,type="response")
pred.gbm <- predict(mod.gbm,
                    newdata=test.df.cv,
                    n.trees=numTreesPred)
mod.gbm.cv <- gbm(dFRS ~.,
                  data=train.df.cv,
                  distribution="gaussian", ## for regression
                  n.trees=numTrees,
                  shrinkage=theShrinkage,
                  interaction.depth = theDepth,
                  n.cores = 4)
gbm.perf(mod.gbm.cv)
## OOB generally underestimates the optimal number of iterations although predictive performance is reasonably competitive. Using cv_folds>1 when calling gbm usually results in improved predictive performance.

## [1] 30
## attr(,"smoother")
## Call:
## loess(formula = object$oobag.improve ~ x, enp.target = min(max(4, 
##     length(x)/10), 50))
## 
## Number of Observations: 1000 
## Equivalent Number of Parameters: 40 
## Residual Standard Error: 0.000183
theShrinkage <- 0.05
mod.gbm.cv <- gbm(dFRS ~.,
                  data=als.df,
                  distribution="gaussian", ## for regression
                  n.trees=numTrees,
                  shrinkage=theShrinkage,
                  interaction.depth = theDepth,

#CV GBM func

cvGBM <- function(data.df,
                  theShrinkage,
                  theDepth,
                  numTreesPred,
                  numFolds=5){
  N <- nrow(data.df)
  folds <- sample(1:numFolds,N,rep=T)
  errs <- numeric(numFolds)
  fold <- 1
  for(fold in 1:numFolds){
    train.df.cv <- als.df[folds != fold,]
    test.df.cv <- als.df[folds == fold,]
    mod.gbm <- gbm(dFRS ~ . ,
                   data=train.df.cv,
                   distribution="gaussian",
                   interaction.depth = theDepth,
                   shrinkage=theShrinkage,
                   n.minobsinnode=10,
                   n.trees=numTrees)
    pred.gbm <- predict(mod.gbm,
                        newdata=test.df.cv,
                        n.trees=numTreesPred)
    errs[fold] <- with(test.df.cv,mean((dFRS-pred.gbm)^2))
  }
  mean(errs)
}
